FordGoBike Exploration¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing information on Ford Go Bikes in the California Bay area, such as the distance and duration of travel, amongst other attributes.

# We have to change the columns indicated below to the correct datatype before contnuing.
ford['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(ford['start_time'])
ford['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(ford['end_time'])
ford['start_station_name'] = ford['start_station_name'].astype('category')
ford['end_station_name'] = ford['end_station_name'].astype('category')
ford['user_type'] = ford['user_type'].astype('category')
ford['member_gender'] = ford['member_gender'].astype('category')
ford['bike_share_for_all_trip'] = ford['bike_share_for_all_trip'].astype('category')
ford['start_station_id'] = ford['start_station_id'].astype('str')
ford['end_station_id'] = ford['end_station_id'].astype('str')
ford['bike_id'] = ford['bike_id'].astype('str')
In [123]:
# We want to create new columns to aid visualizations
ford['start_hour'] = ford.start_time.dt.strftime('%H')
ford['start_day'] = ford.start_time.dt.strftime('%A')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In total the dataset contains recordings for 183412 trips with 16 columns of data. After removal of null values, and the restriction of age values, the dataset contains 174749 values. Of the numeric variables, we have a few discrete, such as age and start time, and a continuous 'duration' variable. We also have 5 variables of interest that have been corrected to nominal categorical variables rather than strings.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features have the most effect on the duration of cyles.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Realistically, I think gender may have some slight differences. I think age will play a part as well, although it's difficult to say excatly what effect it will have. Day of the week will most likely show some correlation, perhaps with people cycling longer on work days, and also time, as people are less likely to cycle in evenings rather than mornings etc. I also think subscribers will probably cycle longer as they may use it to get to work.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the faceted graph I saw that the duration for bike sharers compared to non-bike sharing customers was actually a lot more evident than it was just with non-bike sharers, as the effect of work travel on non bike sharing subscribers caused a reduction in the means calculated in the bivariate plot. The distribution of longer durations for customers also gave us a better understanding of that disparity in mean values calculated in the bivariate exploration, and it appears a higher proportion of people over 40 go on longer duration cycles, again in part due to the effect of lower duration cycles amongst young workers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was surprising to see the bike share for all trip actually decrease in comparison to average duration for non subscribers who didn't bike share, especially given bike sharing didn't show much correlation with the 'rush hour' pattern. Given this, I would have expected people who bike share to make up longer duration leisurely cycles, and thus for the faceted graph to show at least a few long duration cycles. In fact there were very few above 10,000, as opposed to non-bike sharing customers, who frequently exceeded this duration.
